                        "type": "0",
                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "The nurse is providing care for a client recently admitted with new-onset pleurisy. Upon auscultation of the client's lungs, the nurse notes an absence of the pleural friction rub that was documented on previous assessments. What is the most likely indication for this change in the client's lung sounds?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nPleural friction rub is auscultated early in the course of pleurisy before pleural fluid accumulates. Once fluid accumulates in the inflamed area, friction between the visceral and parietal lung surfaces decreases, and the pleural friction rub disappears. The remaining options are incorrect interpretations.",
                        "id": "8e4f104d0156481ea3fee07142964f4a",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
